450
00:25:28.487 --> 00:25:30.446
[Ben] I'm sure he would be.

451
00:25:30.447 --> 00:25:33.741
but he's already accepted a
position as Youth Rabbi in Miami.

452
00:25:33.742 --> 00:25:37.703
Dad. I don't want to move back to Florida.
How many times do I gotta tell you?

453
00:25:37.704 --> 00:25:42.208
There are people in Miami. people with
whom I have long relationships with.

454
00:25:42.209 --> 00:25:44.168
who are offering
Marshall an opportunity.

455
00:25:44.169 --> 00:25:48.048
You can't turn it off for
even a single moment. Ben.

456
00:25:50.259 --> 00:25:53.804
The joke about the rocks. I
taught him that. Excuse me.

457
00:25:55.472 --> 00:25:56.473
Hello. Junior.

458
00:25:57.349 --> 00:26:01.477
I think when he sees the work that
you've done. he'll understand.

459
00:26:01.478 --> 00:26:02.813
Let's hope so.

460
00:26:03.564 --> 00:26:06.482
- I wanna go fix my face. It's so hot here.
- [Marshall] Yeah.

461
00:26:06.483 --> 00:26:09.194
- [laughs. coughs] Excuse me.
- All right. Mom.

462
00:26:10.445 --> 00:26:12.489
Wait. I'm confused.
You're going to Florida?

463
00:26:13.073 --> 00:26:13.907
Yes. sir.

464
00:26:13.908 --> 00:26:15.992
[Junior] <i>How do I get the
Chinese out of my Arctic?</i>

465
00:26:15.993 --> 00:26:18.870
The Chinese? I know
nothing about the Chinese.

466
00:26:18.871 --> 00:26:20.788
<i>Well. they're parked out
in the bay. taunting me.</i>

467
00:26:20.789 --> 00:26:24.458
Junior. I'm not a lawyer. I'm
just your business manager.

468
00:26:24.459 --> 00:26:28.713
But if they're not actually on the
island. they may be within their rights.

469
00:26:28.714 --> 00:26:31.007
<i>It sounds like we may
have a real problem here</i>

470
00:26:31.008 --> 00:26:33.259
- <i>with the Arctic Council.</i>
- Ben. Ben. Ben.

471
00:26:33.260 --> 00:26:36.012
You don't call Bilton with problems.
you call him with solutions.

472
00:26:36.013 --> 00:26:37.890
which is why I just
called my sister.

473
00:26:38.390 --> 00:26:40.976
[panting]

474
00:26:43.312 --> 00:26:46.564
Yes. I know Bilton is the
richest man on earth. I do.

475
00:26:46.565 --> 00:26:51.527
but what I don't know is if that puts
him in a position to change treaties.

476
00:26:51.528 --> 00:26:56.782
Help! Somebody call a
doctor! Hurry. now. Please.

477
00:26:56.783 --> 00:26:59.368
[Junior] <i>Ben. He's
Nicholas fucking Bilton.</i>

478
00:26:59.369 --> 00:27:01.830
<i>He can change you and
I into poor people.</i>

479
00:27:03.373 --> 00:27:06.000
[Marshall] Mom? Mom.
can you hear me?

480
00:27:06.001 --> 00:27:07.919
Hey. Mom. squeeze my
hand if you can hear me.

481
00:27:07.920 --> 00:27:09.420
- Hey. Mama. Mom.
- [Ben] Isabel.

482
00:27:09.421 --> 00:27:11.130
I-Is-Is somebody coming?

483
00:27:11.131 --> 00:27:12.841
[Marshall] Dad. do something!

484
00:27:13.383 --> 00:27:15.009
Get... Get help! Mom!

485
00:27:15.010 --> 00:27:16.928
[bystander] She
has a pulse. Rabbi.

486
00:27:16.929 --> 00:27:20.139
Come on. Mom. Mom. stay with me.

487
00:27:20.140 --> 00:27:22.266
- [device beeps]
- [guide] <i>It's all going as planned.</i>

488
00:27:22.267 --> 00:27:26.145
<i>He's still under the impression that
you are interested in the hotel business</i>

489
00:27:26.146 --> 00:27:28.147
<i>rather than what's
beneath the ground.</i>

490
00:27:28.148 --> 00:27:29.941
<i>Quite frankly. he is clueless.</i>

491
00:27:29.942 --> 00:27:33.236
<i>All we need now is UN approval.</i>

492
00:27:33.237 --> 00:27:34.570
<i>O-One more thing. sir.</i>

493
00:27:34.571 --> 00:27:37.406
<i>Do you know if he's romantically
involved with the woman trav...</i>

494
00:27:37.407 --> 00:27:39.493
- [groans] Delete message.
- [device beeps]

495
00:27:40.369 --> 00:27:42.453
[electronic voice] <i>Chief
Counsel Hampton for you.</i>

496
00:27:42.454 --> 00:27:43.747
Send them in.

497
00:27:48.335 --> 00:27:50.879
[Hampton] Are we really
considering waiving our patents?

498
00:27:51.672 --> 00:27:53.257
Have you seen what's happening?

499
00:28:00.180 --> 00:28:01.223
Markets. please.

500
00:28:06.270 --> 00:28:11.859
Nickel is up 5.6%. Cobalt
up 7.7. Copper. way up.

501
00:28:12.693 --> 00:28:13.985
All the base metals.

502
00:28:13.986 --> 00:28:17.446
You were right. It's the fires.

503
00:28:17.447 --> 00:28:22.410
The world is a desperate but predictable
animal. And it wants to run on batteries.

504
00:28:22.411 --> 00:28:24.329
That makes Tel Aviv easier.

505
00:28:25.998 --> 00:28:30.294
It's all just one giant. self-regulatory.
living feedback loop. isn't it?

506
00:28:32.880 --> 00:28:34.089
Greenland. please.

507
00:28:35.215 --> 00:28:38.969
{\an8}And here we have our ice turning
into water. Adirondacks. please.

508
00:28:40.137 --> 00:28:41.471
{\an8}Trees turning into fire.

509
00:28:42.848 --> 00:28:45.017
The solution miles
from the problem.

510
00:28:46.059 --> 00:28:48.645
Or it's all just
chaos out there.

511
00:28:53.108 --> 00:28:55.068
Either view presents
us an opportunity.

512
00:28:57.196 --> 00:29:01.033
The man whose house is on fire is
incredibly easy to negotiate with. Mikey.

513
00:29:01.867 --> 00:29:03.507
Didn't they teach you
that in law school?

514
00:29:04.203 --> 00:29:05.204
[chuckles]

515
00:29:05.996 --> 00:29:07.998
[inhales deeply] Time to go.

516
00:29:23.138 --> 00:29:25.014
[Junior] Yeah. it's your
brother calling again.

517
00:29:25.015 --> 00:29:28.559
Did you know that China has a
permanent seat on the Arctic Council?

518
00:29:28.560 --> 00:29:30.186
- Did you?
- Do you expect me to wear this?

519
00:29:30.187 --> 00:29:31.562
Call me back.

520
00:29:31.563 --> 00:29:33.022
- [Hannah] Do you?
- Uh. that depends.

521
00:29:33.023 --> 00:29:34.649
Do you really
expect to get paid?

522
00:29:34.650 --> 00:29:37.860
Because if you do. let me remind you
of the deal that we both agreed on.

523
00:29:37.861 --> 00:29:39.904
You would dress up as
a Christmas ornament.

524
00:29:39.905 --> 00:29:41.489
sing your little song.
do your little dance.

525
00:29:41.490 --> 00:29:43.950
I stick a shovel in the
ground. we all go home.

526
00:29:43.951 --> 00:29:47.703
Next year. when you have a
100-night residency at my casino.

527
00:29:47.704 --> 00:29:49.330
wear what the fuck you want.

528
00:29:49.331 --> 00:29:52.417
As long as you don't run
afoul of a global superpower.

529
00:29:53.710 --> 00:29:55.044
What are you doing?

530
00:29:55.045 --> 00:29:56.379
I wanted that one.

531
00:29:56.380 --> 00:29:59.633
[laughs] Th... That one?

532
00:30:00.884 --> 00:30:03.094
Oh. okay. Uh. I'll
get you another one.

533
00:30:03.095 --> 00:30:05.304
In fact. you can have any rock
you want on the fucking island

534
00:30:05.305 --> 00:30:06.889
as long as it fits on the plane.

535
00:30:06.890 --> 00:30:08.058
It was gold.

536
00:30:10.018 --> 00:30:12.812
- What?
- Yeah. Jordan gave it to me.

537
00:30:12.813 --> 00:30:15.231
He says it's everywhere. if
you know where to look for it.

538
00:30:15.232 --> 00:30:19.361
Gold. copper. nickel. Yeah.
and there's one other one.

539
00:30:22.030 --> 00:30:23.156
[sighs]

540
00:30:27.995 --> 00:30:29.495
[Marshall. in Hebrew]
<i>Thank you. Doctor.</i>

541
00:30:29.496 --> 00:30:32.749
I'm sorry I don't
have better news.

542
00:30:40.465 --> 00:30:43.968
[Marshall. in English] Um. here's
what the doctor's saying. Dad.

543
00:30:43.969 --> 00:30:48.473
[inhales deeply] She has a subdural
hematoma from the fall. Okay?

544
00:30:49.266 --> 00:30:53.269
Um. her temporal lobe
appears to be involved.

545
00:30:53.270 --> 00:30:55.355
so that is why she can't speak.

546
00:30:56.440 --> 00:30:59.151
And so far. the extent
of the damage is unclear.

547
00:31:02.154 --> 00:31:03.363
I'm sorry. Dad.

548
00:31:08.785 --> 00:31:11.537
- Dad. do you understand the. uh...
- [mouthing] I'm on the phone.

549
00:31:11.538 --> 00:31:16.000
[Ben] Just pull everything we have on
the Arctic development deal. Everything.

550
00:31:16.001 --> 00:31:19.670
As well as all relevant
law of the sea statutes.

551
00:31:19.671 --> 00:31:21.923
- Yes. and...
- Dad. Dad! Hang up the phone!

552
00:31:21.924 --> 00:31:26.177
Marshall! That man and his family
have been a client for 25 years!

553
00:31:26.178 --> 00:31:31.599
Twenty... That woman upstairs who
can't move has been your wife for 40!

554
00:31:31.600 --> 00:31:34.686
[Ben] What? Marshall. where
are you going? Marshall!

555
00:31:36.688 --> 00:31:37.689
[sighs]

556
00:31:48.659 --> 00:31:50.160
[sighs. sniffs]

557
00:31:51.161 --> 00:31:52.454
Are you still there?

558
00:32:00.629 --> 00:32:02.297
[ice cracking]

559
00:32:12.516 --> 00:32:14.851
[narrator] <i>We may not be
able to stop extinction.</i>

560
00:32:14.852 --> 00:32:17.396
<i>but what if we could bring
these creatures back?</i>

561
00:32:18.313 --> 00:32:20.857
<i>Using the latest
genomic technology.</i>

562
00:32:20.858 --> 00:32:24.694
{\an8}<i>Menagerie2100 will save
what nature cannot.</i>

563
00:32:24.695 --> 00:32:29.073
<i>We are committed to gene-capturing
the animals and plants you love.</i>

564
00:32:29.074 --> 00:32:31.118
<i>and the ones you
never think about.</i>

565
00:32:32.494 --> 00:32:34.871
<i>We project that by the
end of the century.</i>

566
00:32:34.872 --> 00:32:40.209
<i>Menagerie2100 will be able to maintain
a vast library of all species.</i>

567
00:32:40.210 --> 00:32:43.713
<i>preparing for the day when they
can be reintroduced to zoos.</i>

568
00:32:43.714 --> 00:32:46.466
<i>parks and someday even the w...</i>

569
00:32:51.263 --> 00:32:56.727
[Becca] Lack of oxygen.
hypoxia. He wanted to come out.

570
00:32:57.936 --> 00:32:59.855
Feel like he was safer inside.

571
00:33:01.148 --> 00:33:03.192
He's lucky he has
such a strong mother.

572
00:33:04.067 --> 00:33:05.152
[phone beeps]

573
00:33:06.361 --> 00:33:07.696
Oh. he landed. [sighs]

574
00:33:08.780 --> 00:33:09.907
He'll be here soon.

575
00:33:11.867 --> 00:33:13.743
Thank you so much for staying.

576
00:33:13.744 --> 00:33:14.995
[baby cooing]

577
00:33:22.836 --> 00:33:24.046
Can I ask you something?

578
00:33:24.838 --> 00:33:25.839
Sure.

579
00:33:27.090 --> 00:33:28.550
On the helicopter.

580
00:33:30.010 --> 00:33:33.388
you said you interviewed
with Menagerie2100.

581
00:33:35.307 --> 00:33:37.809
So they decide what
species survive?

582
00:33:38.644 --> 00:33:41.813
- Give up on now. Hope for the future.
- [sighs]

583
00:33:42.689 --> 00:33:44.816
And you wanna help with that?

584
00:33:46.610 --> 00:33:50.364
Come on. I mean.
you see the numbers.

585
00:33:51.031 --> 00:33:53.366
The ravens are going away.

586
00:33:53.367 --> 00:33:54.993
The bees are almost gone.

587
00:33:56.745 --> 00:33:59.331
We're on track to lose a
third of life on Earth.

588
00:34:00.123 --> 00:34:02.292
Everyone wants to play
God but God. I guess.

589
00:34:03.043 --> 00:34:06.463
Maybe it's better than playing
funeral director for the Park Service.

590
00:34:07.589 --> 00:34:08.590
I don't know.

591
00:34:18.641 --> 00:34:22.563
The fires are spreading
further north.

592
00:34:23.730 --> 00:34:25.732
All the way up to
Whitefeather Forest.

593
00:34:26.900 --> 00:34:28.651
- They're evacuating Pikangikum.
- Oh. my God.

594
00:34:28.652 --> 00:34:31.028
My mother wants to know
where she can go that's safe.

595
00:34:31.029 --> 00:34:32.238
[Becca sighs]

596
00:34:32.239 --> 00:34:36.243
I'm not sure safe
exists anymore.

597
00:34:41.456 --> 00:34:42.583
Here. take this.

598
00:34:44.208 --> 00:34:45.210
I think it helped.

599
00:34:45.918 --> 00:34:46.920
Keep it.

600
00:34:48.088 --> 00:34:51.507
Ask your friends at Menagerie if
they have a plan to bring us back.

601
00:34:57.014 --> 00:35:00.767
[door opens. closes]

602
00:35:02.144 --> 00:35:03.437
[Hannah] Ow. Shit.

603
00:35:04.062 --> 00:35:06.690
So. are we groundbreaking
or rock collecting?

604
00:35:07.733 --> 00:35:12.737
Nickel. copper. what was the
third? Cobalt? Was it cobalt?

605
00:35:12.738 --> 00:35:15.114
- I don't remember.
- Because that's why the Chinese showed up.

606
00:35:15.115 --> 00:35:17.366
Batteries. That's what
they want. batteries.

607
00:35:17.367 --> 00:35:19.118
That look like copper
to you? That line?

608
00:35:19.119 --> 00:35:22.623
I don't know. I'm not a miner.
I'm a singer and an actress.

609
00:35:23.123 --> 00:35:24.123
Great.

610
00:35:24.124 --> 00:35:27.210
Then there's just a chance I'm wandering
around a beach staring at fucking rocks.

611
00:35:27.211 --> 00:35:32.006
[smacks lips] Here's an idea. why
don't you ask somebody who knows?

612
00:35:32.007 --> 00:35:33.799
How come Jordan
knows and you don't?

613
00:35:33.800 --> 00:35:37.178
Okay. So. if Jordan
knows. Bilton knows.

614
00:35:37.179 --> 00:35:42.308
And I b... I bet you our deal is just for
hospitality development only. not mining.

615
00:35:42.309 --> 00:35:44.602
Then we're out.

616
00:35:44.603 --> 00:35:46.437
We're just out. Lost
between the laws.

617
00:35:46.438 --> 00:35:50.191
Just bent over by the fine
print. Castrated by contracts.

618
00:35:50.192 --> 00:35:53.779
'Cause who's going to stay in a hotel
with a view of a fucking copper mine?

619
00:35:56.990 --> 00:35:58.700
So does this mean
I'm not singing?

620
00:36:01.328 --> 00:36:04.248
[Becca] That line there.
that's the heart monitor.

621
00:36:06.083 --> 00:36:08.252
I don't know. They
seem really concerned.

622
00:36:10.796 --> 00:36:14.132
We knew the risks. Becca. We
are all filled with plastic now.

623
00:36:16.134 --> 00:36:18.053
Maybe my sperm is defective.

624
00:36:19.012 --> 00:36:20.597
No. I don't think this was you.

625
00:36:22.558 --> 00:36:24.225
I think I did this to him.

626
00:36:24.226 --> 00:36:25.310
Did what?

627
00:36:26.144 --> 00:36:27.187
He's here.

628
00:36:28.647 --> 00:36:31.275
I'm here. You're here.

629
00:36:34.236 --> 00:36:37.155
I was out in the
woods saving birds.

630
00:36:39.116 --> 00:36:40.909
I should have been
protecting him.

631
00:36:41.618 --> 00:36:44.705
And I left a climate summit
to be with my family.

632
00:36:49.877 --> 00:36:51.003
Are we bad people?

633
00:36:53.255 --> 00:36:54.673
[chuckles]

634
00:36:56.383 --> 00:36:59.595
I guess we can ask
him when he grows up.

635
00:37:03.098 --> 00:37:04.725
- [baby cries]
- It's okay.

636
00:37:08.395 --> 00:37:09.396
Okay.

637
00:37:14.359 --> 00:37:18.029
I called the chairman of the
board at Temple Israel in Miami.

638
00:37:18.030 --> 00:37:21.365
They want to introduce you
officially to the congregation

639
00:37:21.366 --> 00:37:22.992
- during the High Holidays.
- Dad.

640
00:37:22.993 --> 00:37:24.118
I bought you a ticket.

641
00:37:24.119 --> 00:37:26.913
but they're gonna need your passport
number and your vaccine status.

642
00:37:26.914 --> 00:37:30.959
- because goddamn dengue is back and...
- Dad. can you listen to me for one minute?

643
00:37:33.629 --> 00:37:37.174
There are people here
who depend on me.

644
00:37:39.635 --> 00:37:41.094
You saw those kids.

645
00:37:42.054 --> 00:37:44.555
You have a mother
who's in the hospital.

646
00:37:44.556 --> 00:37:46.933
She's got a brain injury.
She can't use her arms.

647
00:37:46.934 --> 00:37:48.768
She can't form sentences.

648
00:37:48.769 --> 00:37:52.021
She's gonna need a great
deal of care back in Miami.

649
00:37:52.022 --> 00:37:53.272
I understand.

650
00:37:53.273 --> 00:37:57.109
Do you? Do you. Marshall? Do you
know how much that woman loves you?

651
00:37:57.110 --> 00:37:59.862
Because if you did. you
would come back home with us.

652
00:37:59.863 --> 00:38:00.947
I love her.

653
00:38:00.948 --> 00:38:02.573
"Honor your father
and your mother.

654
00:38:02.574 --> 00:38:05.701
so your days may be long upon the
land of the Lord your God gives you."

655
00:38:05.702 --> 00:38:09.830
Dad. what is happening right now? You're
quoting the Ten Commandments to me.

656
00:38:09.831 --> 00:38:11.374
Do you r-realize that...

657
00:38:11.375 --> 00:38:15.211
That she would never even have been
here walking around through the smoke

658
00:38:15.212 --> 00:38:17.005
if it wasn't for you?

659
00:38:20.843 --> 00:38:25.556
[scoffs] Ooh. Dad. [sniffles]

660
00:38:27.140 --> 00:38:29.268
Glad she didn't have
to hear you say that.

661
00:38:30.018 --> 00:38:34.272
I really am glad that her brain does not
have to try and make sense of that one.

662
00:38:34.273 --> 00:38:35.566
because mine sure can't.

663
00:38:36.733 --> 00:38:38.150
She needs you.

664
00:38:38.151 --> 00:38:39.736
[Marshall] You
gonna answer that?

665
00:38:40.821 --> 00:38:41.864
Are you?

666
00:38:46.159 --> 00:38:47.619
I need you!

667
00:38:54.126 --> 00:38:55.919
- [sighs]
- [door closes]

668
00:38:56.837 --> 00:38:58.297
[crying]

669
00:39:03.677 --> 00:39:08.682
[breathing heavily]
I need you! [cries]

670
00:39:10.225 --> 00:39:12.768
[protesters] The world is on
fire! And Bilton is a liar!

671
00:39:12.769 --> 00:39:14.605
<i>Hell is upon us.
ladies and gentlemen.</i>

672
00:39:15.314 --> 00:39:16.898
<i>We are living in a disco inferno</i>

673
00:39:16.899 --> 00:39:20.110
<i>where the music is cooking on a
dance floor right beneath our feet.</i>

674
00:39:20.777 --> 00:39:24.322
<i>The oven below is slow and low.
and we are still not learning.</i>

675
00:39:24.323 --> 00:39:26.617
{\an8}<i>Where did the
undying yearning go?</i>

676
00:39:27.826 --> 00:39:29.036
<i>2 degrees.</i>

677
00:39:29.620 --> 00:39:33.290
<i>2 degrees will cook
the fool out of you.</i>

678
00:39:34.082 --> 00:39:35.249
<i>What are you willing to do?</i>

679
00:39:35.250 --> 00:39:36.584
[protestor] The world's on fire!

680
00:39:36.585 --> 00:39:38.065
[speaker] <i>What are
you willing to do?</i>

681
00:39:38.837 --> 00:39:40.213
<i>Net-zero now...</i>

682
00:39:40.214 --> 00:39:41.339
How many more?

683
00:39:41.340 --> 00:39:43.341
- [speaker] <i>Don't give a fuck about how.</i>
- [officer] Hey. sir.

684
00:39:43.342 --> 00:39:45.801
- [speaker] <i>Net-zero now.</i>
- Net-zero.

685
00:39:45.802 --> 00:39:47.637
[speaker] <i>I say. save
the planet somehow.</i>

686
00:39:47.638 --> 00:39:49.472
- What's it gonna take?
- [speaker] <i>Net-zero now.</i>

687
00:39:49.473 --> 00:39:51.683
<i>I say. save the planet somehow.</i>

688
00:39:52.351 --> 00:39:54.645
<i>Or it will save itself from you.</i>

689
00:39:56.355 --> 00:39:58.064
[reporter] <i>I spoke
privately to a delegate</i>

690
00:39:58.065 --> 00:40:02.485
who expressed their frustration as
we enter the final evening of COP42.

691
00:40:02.486 --> 00:40:05.029
where the real possibility of
raising the temperature ceiling

692
00:40:05.030 --> 00:40:09.367
above the previously agreed
upon limit is now up for debate.

693
00:40:09.368 --> 00:40:12.286
Both the United States and China.
as well as Russia and India.

694
00:40:12.287 --> 00:40:13.579
seem open to this idea...

695
00:40:13.580 --> 00:40:15.456
I wanted to tell you
how I decided to vote.

696
00:40:15.457 --> 00:40:17.751
It's all become
very complicated.

697
00:40:18.544 --> 00:40:22.756
What does that mean. "complicated"?
What decision did you make?

698
00:40:24.591 --> 00:40:26.551
[sighs] I think I may
have made a mistake.

699
00:40:26.552 --> 00:40:27.952
[announcer] <i>Please
make your way...</i>

700
00:40:28.971 --> 00:40:32.683
You need to tell me. what
decision did you make?

701
00:40:33.934 --> 00:40:36.645
[voter] <i>I fear I traded
the future for the present.</i>

702
00:40:37.646 --> 00:40:40.523
- <i>I agreed to an increase.</i>
- [sighs]

703
00:40:40.524 --> 00:40:42.066
[protestors shouting]

704
00:40:42.067 --> 00:40:46.028
[protesters] The world is on
fire! And Bilton is a liar!

705
00:40:46.029 --> 00:40:48.782
[Mikey] It's done. All parties
agreed to our proposal.

706
00:40:49.283 --> 00:40:50.826
Exemptions for patents.

707
00:40:51.785 --> 00:40:54.538
You never really cared
about the casino.

708
00:40:55.747 --> 00:40:58.041
The whole island could
end up underwater.

709
00:40:58.917 --> 00:41:02.713
My father liked to gamble. I used to
go with him to Monaco when I was young.

710
00:41:03.672 --> 00:41:06.257
He thought he was so very
clever when he beat the odds.

711
00:41:06.258 --> 00:41:08.384
More clever. I think.
to control the odds.

712
00:41:08.385 --> 00:41:11.680
[protesters shouting. chanting]

713
00:41:14.224 --> 00:41:17.769
The lawyers would like you not to
mention the Arctic mining exemptions.

714
00:41:18.478 --> 00:41:20.354
at least not until
after the vote.

715
00:41:20.355 --> 00:41:24.150
Of course not. Today's not about
the exemptions. Today's about water.

716
00:41:24.151 --> 00:41:28.030
and how Alpha is solving the drought
and the resulting refugee problem.

717
00:41:28.530 --> 00:41:30.072
- Tomorrow. however...
- The world is on fire!

718
00:41:30.073 --> 00:41:31.699
And Bilton is a liar!

719
00:41:31.700 --> 00:41:34.452
[protestors shouting. chanting]

720
00:41:34.453 --> 00:41:35.828
Hey. Bilton!

721
00:41:35.829 --> 00:41:37.496
[protestors] The world is on
fire! And Bilton is a liar!

722
00:41:37.497 --> 00:41:39.166
This is on you!

723
00:41:42.461 --> 00:41:44.630
[crowd screaming]

724
00:41:48.509 --> 00:41:49.509
Fuck.

725
00:41:51.053 --> 00:41:54.848
[Becca] <i>When Raven saw the sun and
moon and stars and fresh water.</i>

726
00:41:55.724 --> 00:41:57.267
he knew what he should do.

727
00:42:00.604 --> 00:42:02.147
<i>He waited for his chance.</i>

728
00:42:03.482 --> 00:42:05.192
<i>And when no one was looking.</i>

729
00:42:06.318 --> 00:42:08.237
he stole all of them.

730
00:42:09.196 --> 00:42:10.906
And a brand of fire too.

731
00:42:14.034 --> 00:42:16.286
<i>It made so much light.</i>

732
00:42:17.162 --> 00:42:18.872
I don't know what to do. Mom.

733
00:42:22.125 --> 00:42:25.963
[Becca] <i>That he was able to
fly far out to an island...</i>

734
00:42:29.466 --> 00:42:31.093
<i>in the middle of the ocean.</i>

735
00:42:33.011 --> 00:42:34.721
<i>And when the sun set...</i>

736
00:42:37.140 --> 00:42:39.601
<i>he fastened the
moon up in the sky</i>

737
00:42:41.061 --> 00:42:43.604
<i>and hung the stars around
in different places.</i>

738
00:42:43.605 --> 00:42:44.690
[Junior scoffs]

739
00:42:45.274 --> 00:42:46.275
Bullshit.

740
00:42:46.942 --> 00:42:48.860
And then when he
flew over the land.

741
00:42:48.861 --> 00:42:51.572
he dropped all the
water he had stolen.

742
00:42:52.906 --> 00:42:54.282
It fell to the ground

743
00:42:54.283 --> 00:42:58.829
and became the source of all the
streams and lakes in the world.

744
00:43:00.914 --> 00:43:02.332
And then Raven flew on.

745
00:43:03.709 --> 00:43:08.838
The smoke from the fire he was
carrying blew over his white feathers

746
00:43:08.839 --> 00:43:10.299
and turned them black.

747
00:43:11.842 --> 00:43:14.595
And when his bill began to
burn. he dropped the fire.

748
00:43:17.055 --> 00:43:21.852
Raven's feathers never were white again
once they'd been blackened by the smoke.

749
00:43:24.271 --> 00:43:26.523
And that is why Raven
is a black bird.

750
00:43:29.693 --> 00:43:30.903
I like that story.

751
00:43:33.363 --> 00:43:36.283
It isn't mine. I borrowed
it from a friend.

752
00:43:39.578 --> 00:43:40.704
Bullshit.

753
00:43:46.502 --> 00:43:47.669
[sighs]

754
00:43:50.756 --> 00:43:52.216
[walrus grunting]

755
00:43:52.925 --> 00:43:53.926
[chuckles]

756
00:43:54.468 --> 00:43:56.136
[walrus barking]

757
00:44:00.057 --> 00:44:03.185
- [walrus barking]
- [Junior] You are one lucky walrus.

758
00:44:04.186 --> 00:44:08.689
If I had my gun. you would
be... [imitates gunshot]

759
00:44:08.690 --> 00:44:10.526
[walrus growling]

760
00:44:18.992 --> 00:44:21.744
- [walrus growls]
- [Junior screaming]

761
00:44:21.745 --> 00:44:22.829
[flesh tearing]

762
00:44:25.123 --> 00:44:26.124
[phone beeps]

763
00:44:33.298 --> 00:44:34.675
[walrus snorts]

764
00:44:35.968 --> 00:44:38.845
[walrus barking]

765
00:44:38.846 --> 00:44:42.348
[protesters chanting] If we go
to 2. it's the end of me and you!

766
00:44:42.349 --> 00:44:44.600
If we go to 2. it's the end...

767
00:44:44.601 --> 00:44:48.564
[crowd applauding. booing]

768
00:44:57.614 --> 00:44:58.782
Good evening. everyone.

769
00:44:59.741 --> 00:45:05.414
It is an honor to be here and to be
included in these vital conversations.

770
00:45:06.206 --> 00:45:08.082
Around the turn of this century.

771
00:45:08.083 --> 00:45:12.671
climate change was described
as a symptom of capitalism.

772
00:45:13.422 --> 00:45:14.464
A symptom.

773
00:45:15.549 --> 00:45:19.469
I am here to suggest that
capitalism is also the cure.

774
00:45:20.721 --> 00:45:26.642
So. today I can announce that I will
make the patents for desalinization

775
00:45:26.643 --> 00:45:31.898
and purification of water available to
any country that can demonstrate the need.

776
00:45:31.899 --> 00:45:33.650
[crowd applauding]

777
00:45:35.903 --> 00:45:36.945
Additionally...

778
00:45:39.198 --> 00:45:43.201
Additionally. Alpha will
join the Tel Aviv Accord

779
00:45:43.202 --> 00:45:47.079
in committing to keeping the global
temperature increase in this century

780
00:45:47.080 --> 00:45:50.167
as close to 2 degrees
Celsius as possible.

781
00:45:50.918 --> 00:45:56.048
- With a ceiling of 2.3 degrees.
- [crowd booing. applauding]

782
00:46:07.392 --> 00:46:08.393
Thank you.

783
00:46:33.126 --> 00:46:37.004
{\an8}<i>What does an increase in global
temperatures by 2 degrees Celsius</i>

784
00:46:37.005 --> 00:46:39.216
<i>mean to you and me?</i>

785
00:46:39.800 --> 00:46:41.884
<i>It means that when the
temperature goes up.</i>

786
00:46:41.885 --> 00:46:44.763
<i>our imagination must
increase even more.</i>

787
00:46:46.473 --> 00:46:51.311
[speaker] <i>It means that when the sea
level rises. we must rise up as well.</i>

788
00:46:52.396 --> 00:46:56.107
<i>It means that when forest
fires obscure the horizon</i>

789
00:46:56.108 --> 00:46:59.820
<i>we must look toward each
other to find our way forward.</i>

790
00:47:00.320 --> 00:47:04.825
{\an8}<i>We cannot give up and go
home for one simple reason.</i>

791
00:47:05.576 --> 00:47:09.996
<i>We already are home.
This is our only home.</i>

792
00:47:09.997 --> 00:47:11.832
[protestors cheering]

793
00:47:16.128 --> 00:47:17.754
<i>We're not fucking giving up.</i>

794
00:47:22.217 --> 00:47:23.218
[sighs]

795
00:47:24.305 --> 00:48:24.595
